name: MG Midget
notes: Rostyle' design wheel for MG Midget. Fits Mini as well. Probably needs banding to take the Mini's low profile tyre (as they seem very smal).

name: Sunraysia
notes: This is the wheel fitted to Mokes from '78 to '79 untill the 1275cc Moke 'Californian' was intruduced which had disc brakes and needed a slightly different wheel to clear the calipers. Compliments from GT mowog in Oz.

name: Sunraysia
notes: Disc brake type wheel. Slightly less 'bulbous' spokes, offset is the same. Compliments from GT mowog in Oz!

name: Weller motorsport
notes: Note: those have 2 PCDs to fit Mini and Ford. Plus some minor differences.

name: Weller
notes: Different style, not dished like Weller 'Motorsport'.

name: Compomotive ML
notes: Note: Look like Alleycat, but spokes are more triangular

name: Minilite
notes: New generation with flat outer lip, undished.

name: ROH
notes: Not 100% sure if they have the 4x4" PCD

name: Sonic
notes: Made in AU.

name: ROVER Sportspack
notes: Genuine wheels can easily be identified. They'r marked as 'Rover' on the rear side (part of the cast). Also the manufacturer, 'Speedline', is named there.

name: Ultralight Extreme
notes: Available in antracite, black and silver

name: Ultralite
notes: Available in antracite, black and silver, various widths

name: VTO 'Classic 8'
notes: From the USA.
Not yet sure if the have a 4x4" PCD.

name: BBS E76
notes: Not yet sure if the have a 4x4" PCD.

name: Mahle / BBS
notes: Not yet sure if the have a 4x4" PCD.

name: Compomotive
notes: Compomotive'stamped to outer rim.

name: ATS
notes: Might have a 100mm PCD.

name: Cheviot 'Turbo'
notes: Made in New Zealand, available in 5", 5.5", 6" up to 7". Not all of them have a 4x4" PCD, but some.

name: Compomotive TH 3pc
notes: Looks very similar to Schmidt TH line. Centres available in gold, black, silver, black or pewter grey.

name: Cosmic RW13
notes: Square cutouts, instead of kidney shaped ones.

name: Cosmic Mk1
notes: Larger cutouts, vents go down a bit.

name: Cosmic Mk1
notes: Ribbed, no 'flat' surface.

name: Cosmic Lega
notes: Not entirely sure yet, if available with 4x4" PCD, but assumed. Made as 5x12" and 3.5&5x10" wheel as well. Note: Not sure of the actual name, maybe it came from the italian 'cerchi in lega' and was assumed as brand-name. Update: Maybe it is a Cosmic wheel! Any confirmation?

name: Cobra 'Drag Slot T.C.'
notes: Made for Hillman Imp. Offset might be not suitable for a Mini. PCD is 4x4".

name: Cragar 'SS'
notes: Made in the USA. Production stopped about 2000. Though Cragar Wheels is still in buiseness with classic 5 spoke wheels with similar design.

name: John Brown Wheels 'D1'
notes: Copy of the old D1. John Brown Wheels is a brand of Midland Wheels

name: Force Racing
notes: Weight: 3.4kg for the 7" wide wheel.

name: Force Racing
notes: Second design.

name: Furmula Jedi
notes: Made exclusively for Formula Jedi single seater race cars.

name: Camille Gotti Design'/OZ?
notes: Not sure, wheter they have a 4" PCD, but assumed.

name: Gotti 073S
notes: PCD could be ordered from 4x95 to 114.3mm. Not initialy a 4x4" wheel!

name: Gotti 5T
notes: PCD could be ordered from 4x95 to 120.6mm. Not initialy a 4x4" wheel!

name: JA Pearce Magna
notes: Note: the wheel has multiple PCDs! From the early 70's.

name: MG Metro Turbo (early)
notes: This is a radial, non-metric wheel. Featuring 4 small covers for the wheel nuts.

name: MG Metro
notes: There are two versions of this wheel; one being a metric 'TD' wheel for Runonflat tyres (R315 160, Denovo succesor). These wheels have a large single cap to cover both center & wheel nuts.

name: MG Metro
notes: Late MG Metro, fitted 1985-87. Part number NAM5849. Note: Those wheels were used on MG Maestros and probably some other models too. Apparently there are two versions of that wheel: metric and non-metric tyre fitment. It's actually between 12 and 13 (R315x120) at around 12.5" dia.

name: MAG Product
notes: Offset probably meant to fit Midget or Hillman Imp in first instance.

name: Mamba
notes: Not 100% sure if it is a 'real' Mamba yet.

name: Mamba replica
notes: This is a replica Mamba wheel sold by MiniMania USA.

name: Mamba 'Solar'
notes: Offset probably meant to fit Midget or Hillman Imp in first instance.

name: Momo/Oscam 'Indianapolis'
notes: This wheel was apparently sold by both Momo & Oscam. Though Momo were true pioneers in 'branding'.

name: Performance wheels [AU], 'Challenger'
notes: Replica of the Globe 'Bathurst' wheel.

name: PLS Silverstone
notes: Free choice of offset

name: Racing Hart
notes: Designeted for local South African market  dual stud pattern, 4x4 and 4x4.5 i.e. Mini and Nissan 1400 ½ ton pickup (based on the old Datsun 120Y)    They look similar to the old Opel Kadet Superboss 15 rim.

name: Rebel
notes: Not intentionally for Mini use, but available with 4x4" PCD.

name: Ronal/Metro Challenge
notes: This was the wheel use for the MG Metro challenge cars.

name: Rial Challenge
notes: Not initially for use with Mini, but available with 4x4" PCD.

name: Schmidt TH Line
notes: 3 piece, from 6-10x13

name: SuperMini
notes: Original design. Available from Sun MOtorsport Iimport Ltd.

name: Compomotive 'Trackstar'/ERA Turbo
notes: The wheel used on the ERA Turbo, made by Compomotive. Exact lettering: 'TRACKSTAR Made in england 6.0Jx13 D1360 ET15'. Under the centre cap is 'COMPOMOTIVE' cast in. Beware: later wheels did not have   the exact lettering as above! ERA's were not equipet with them!

name: Compomotive(?) 'Trackstar'
notes: Seemingly the same as the above ERA wheel, but shows some differences: no manufacturer in the centre and ET22. Lettering: 'TRACKSTAR Made in england 6.0Jx13 ET22*35[38?] D1360[80?]'.

name: Named "Lux" in Rover catalogue
notes: Seemingly the same as used on the ERA Turbo. But with different center cap.    Believed to be made by Compomotive as well, resp. they made a bunch of this wheels for Rover too.

name: Same wheel as above
notes: This one has a different position for the valve!

name: VTO 'Retro 4'
notes: From the USA.

name: GKN
notes: Stock wheel for the Triumph Dolomite Sprint, made by GKN.

name: Wolfrace
notes: Other design...

name: Western Wheels 'Hurricane'/'Cyclone II'
notes: Named 'Cyclone II' in the US, 'Cyclone I' had twice as many spokes. Slotted lugs for multi PCD use.

name: Chevron
notes: Magnesium centre.
